abitation Nation Living together is a typical romantic rite of passage in the United States today. In fact, census data shows a 37 percent increase in couples who choose to commit to and live with one another, forgoing marriage. And yet we know very little about this new “normal” in romantic life. When do people decide to move in together, why do they do so, and what happens to them over time? Drawing on in-depth interviews, Sharon Sassler and Amanda Jayne Miller provide an inside view of how cohabiting relationships play out before and after couples move in together, using couples’ stories to explore the he said/she said of romantic dynamics. Delving into hot-button issues, such as housework, birth control, finances, and expectations for the future, Sassler and Miller deliver surprising insights about the impact of class and education on how relationships unfold. Showcasing the words, thoughts, and conflicts of the couples themselves, Cohabitation Nation offers a riveting and sometimes counterintuitive look at the way we live now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aUnmarried coupleszUnited StatesvInterviews. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  aanthropologists.  acohabitation.  aforgoing marriage.  aliving together.  amillennial relationships.  amoving in together.  apsychologists.  arelationships.  arite of passage.  aromance and dating.  aromantic couples.  ashacking up.  asociologists.1 aMiller, Amanda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052028698640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096210140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962101423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962101